video_description: I was the only Nay on the Ohio House Resolution on Israel. It was not an easy decision to make. No one wants to vote against a resolution condemning violence. But this resolution fell short of what it should have been. To condemn terror but to not ignore the damage and destruction endured by the Palestinian people.  I could not vote ‚ÄòYes‚Äô and abandon my Palestinian friends and neighbors who for too long had very few stand for them.  I still strongly pray for the Jewish lives lost and mourn with my Jewish friends and neighbors as they live through this devastating moment.   But as my friend Rep Isaacsohn stated: It is not moral equivalence to mourn the loss of all innocent lives including those in Gaza.  I cannot in good conscience sit here and vote yes on a resolution that does not ask for a de-escalation of violent retribution launched by Israel against largely civilian territory. The Palestinian children also deserve someone to stand up for them and condemn their murder. Those babies who right now are denied water, electricity and medicine, deserve to have someone stand up for them and condemn their abuse. An abuse they have suffered for over 75 years. With over 6,000 palestinian lives lost since 2008 and thousands more injured and displaced It is time to call for true justice and apply the values of universal human rights to all victims of oppression, regardless of nationality, religion or skin color.  I send my prayers for peace and the protection of innocent lives lost during this conflict. Be it Palestinian, Jewish, American or any other loss of life.  Israeli writer Gideon Levy stated: ‚ÄúWe now have to cry bitterly for the Israeli victims, but we should also cry for Gaza" And finally to quote my favorite verse in the Quran: ‚ÄúO you who believe, be upholders of justice - witnesses for God, even though against (the interest of) yourselves or your parents, and kinsmen.‚Äù 4:135 #freepalestine
